---
/**
 * /pitch — UNLISTED. Linked from the public nav for share-by-link
 * convenience but kept out of search via meta noindex + robots.txt +
 * sitemap filter. Renders without site Nav/Footer (unlisted=true).
 */
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Logo from '../components/Logo.astro';
---
<Base
  title="Pitch — Stryda"
  description="The investor pitch: problem, market, product, GTM, and the round we're raising."
  unlisted={true}
>
  <header class="art-head">
    <div class="container art-head-row">
      <a href="/" class="art-brand" aria-label="Stryda home">
        <Logo size={20} />
        <span class="art-wordmark">stryda</span>
      </a>
      <span class="art-meta">Pitch · 2026 · v1</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <article class="art">
    <div class="container art-container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Investor brief</p>
      <h1 class="h-1 art-h1">
        The AI deal OS for sell-side M&amp;A.
      </h1>
      <p class="art-lede">
        Stryda turns the documents of a sell-side mandate into a draft CIM, teaser, normalized financials, and ranked buyer list in under sixty minutes &mdash; for the boutique investment banks and search funds that run lower-middle-market deals.
      </p>

      <hr class="art-rule" />

      <table class="tbl tldr-tbl">
        <tbody>
          <tr><th scope="row">Wedge</th><td>Workflow copilot for boutique sell-side</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">ICP</th><td>5&ndash;30 person banking teams &middot; sub-$500M revenue mandates &middot; search funds</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Stage</th><td>Closed beta &middot; onboarding ten boutiques in cohorts of three</td></tr>
          <tr><th scope="row">Ask</th><td>Seed round, Q3</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <hr class="art-rule" />

      <section class="seg">
        <p class="eyebrow">01 &middot; The problem</p>
        <h2 class="h-2 art-h2">Forty hours of dead work, per mandate.</h2>
        <p>
          A boutique sell-side associate gets a new mandate on Monday. By Friday they need a teaser. By month-end, a CIM. The financials still need to be normalized. The buyer list still needs to be built. The first version of every output is written from a blank page.
        </p>
        <p>
          Bulge brackets have internal AI tools, research desks, database teams, graphics teams. Boutiques have an associate with Excel, Word, a stack of prior CIMs they're trying not to copy, and the rest of the night. The work is mechanical. The tools are not.
        </p>

        <table class="tbl">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Today, per mandate</th><th>Time spent</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><th scope="row">CIM drafting</th><td>~40 hours</td></tr>
            <tr><th scope="row">Buyer list research</th><td>~12 hours</td></tr>
            <tr><th scope="row">Financial normalization &amp; add-back analysis</th><td>~8 hours</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section class="seg">
        <p class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Market</p>
        <h2 class="h-2 art-h2">Thousands of teams. Almost no tooling.</h2>
        <p>
          The lower-middle-market sell-side advisory world is fragmented and global. Thousands of boutique investment banks, M&amp;A advisory shops, and search funds run real mandates and take real fees. They are too small for bespoke internal tooling and too sophisticated to be served by generic AI products.
        </p>
        <p>
          The total addressable market for a workflow copilot priced at $2&ndash;3k per month per team is meaningful by itself. The strategic upside &mdash; what the workflow product enables once trust is earned &mdash; is the part we are not ready to talk about externally.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="seg">
        <p class="eyebrow">03 &middot; Product</p>
        <h2 class="h-2 art-h2">Four outputs from one ingestion pass.</h2>
        <p>
          A team uploads the documents of a mandate &mdash; financials, management deck, prior CIM. A single ingestion pass produces a draft CIM, a one- to two-page anonymized teaser, normalized financials with add-backs flagged, and a ranked buyer list. Every figure in every output traces back to its source.
        </p>
        <p>
          Quality bar: an associate spends two to four hours editing the CIM, not forty hours writing it. The senior banker still owns voice and emphasis. The first draft is no longer the bottleneck.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="seg">
        <p class="eyebrow">04 &middot; Why now</p>
        <h2 class="h-2 art-h2">Foundation models cleared the bar. The workflow didn't.</h2>
        <p>
          In 2026, an associate at any boutique can paste a 10-K into Claude and get a passable summary. That is not the bottleneck. The bottleneck is the forty-page CIM with consistent voice, the buyer list with named contacts, the financial workbook a senior banker will sign. Every one of those artifacts requires a workflow, not a chatbot.
        </p>
        <p>
          Stryda gets better when the model layer gets better &mdash; and our edge is the part the model never sees: the boutique-specific extraction logic, the document-format awareness, the citation contracts, the export format that fits a banker's muscle memory.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="seg">
        <p class="eyebrow">05 &middot; GTM</p>
        <h2 class="h-2 art-h2">Bottom-up, founder-led, design partners first.</h2>
        <p>
          Ten boutiques in cohorts of three. Ninety days free. Two real mandates. Weekly half-hour with the founding team. We sit next to associates while they use the product. We capture every breakage and every wish.
        </p>
        <p>
          After day ninety: $2&ndash;3k a month per team. No procurement theatre. No SDRs. The associate decides; the partner adopts; the CCO follows. We are explicitly not selling to enterprise buyers in year one.
        </p>

        <table class="tbl">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Phase</th><th>Window</th><th>Focus</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><th scope="row">Phase 1</th><td>0&ndash;6 months</td><td>Ten boutiques. Three cohorts. Workflow product only.</td></tr>
            <tr><th scope="row">Phase 2</th><td>6&ndash;12 months</td><td>Scale to fifty paying boutiques. Sector verticals. CRM integrations.</td></tr>
            <tr><th scope="row">Phase 3</th><td>12 months+</td><td>Strategic surface area we don't talk about externally.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <section class="seg">
        <p class="eyebrow">06 &middot; Defensibility</p>
        <h2 class="h-2 art-h2">Workflow, not model.</h2>
        <p>
          The model layer is interchangeable. The workflow is not. Our edge is the integration of ingestion, extraction, normalization, drafting, and export &mdash; and the per-output telemetry that compounds it deal by deal.
        </p>
        <ul class="dash-list">
          <li><strong>Defensibility:</strong> workflow integration, sector-specific extraction logic, per-output telemetry.</li>
          <li><strong>Distribution:</strong> bottom-up adoption inside teams that lack procurement gates.</li>
          <li><strong>Compliance:</strong> tenant-isolated, encrypted, audit-logged from week one. SOC 2 path on the calendar.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding:</strong> every banker edit is signal. Every regenerate is a labeled example.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="seg">
        <p class="eyebrow">07 &middot; Team</p>
        <h2 class="h-2 art-h2">Founding team.</h2>
        <p>
          Small, technical, sell-side adjacent. We talk to bankers weekly. We ship features they ask for. We do not ship features they don't.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="seg">
        <p class="eyebrow">08 &middot; The ask</p>
        <h2 class="h-2 art-h2">Seed round, Q3.</h2>
        <p>
          We are raising a seed round to bring on the first two engineers and run the design-partner program for ninety days. If you back vertical AI for regulated workflows, we'd like to talk.
        </p>
        <div class="art-cta">
          <a href="mailto:bobbyzli@berkeley.edu" class="btn">Email founders</a>
          <a href="/manifesto" class="btn-link">Read the manifesto</a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <hr class="art-rule" />

      <p class="art-fine">
        This page is a share-by-link artifact. It is excluded from sitemaps and not indexed. All figures on this page are illustrative. No information here constitutes an offer to sell securities.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <footer class="art-foot">
    <div class="container art-foot-row">
      <span>© 2026 Stryda Capital, Inc.</span>
      <span>Share by link &middot; not indexed</span>
    </div>
  </footer>
</Base>

<style>
  .art-head {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--c-line);
    padding: var(--s-5) 0;
  }
  .art-head-row {
    display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between;
  }
  .art-brand {
    display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 10px;
    color: var(--c-fg);
  }
  .art-wordmark {
    font-family: var(--t-sans); font-size: 14px; font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--c-fg);
  }
  .art-meta {
    font-family: var(--t-mono); font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em; text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--c-fg-2);
  }

  .art {
    padding: clamp(64px, 9vw, 128px) 0 var(--s-9);
  }
  .art-container { max-width: 760px; }
  .art-h1 { margin-top: var(--s-4); max-width: 16ch; }
  .art-lede {
    font-size: clamp(18px, 2.4vw, 24px);
    line-height: 1.45;
    color: var(--c-fg-1);
    margin: var(--s-7) 0 0;
    max-width: 42ch;
  }
  .art-rule { margin: var(--s-9) 0; }

  .tldr-tbl tbody th { width: 25%; }

  .seg { margin-top: var(--s-9); }
  .seg .eyebrow { margin-bottom: var(--s-3); }
  .art-h2 {
    margin: var(--s-3) 0 var(--s-5);
    max-width: 28ch;
  }
  .art p { margin: 0 0 var(--s-4); }

  .art-cta {
    display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: var(--s-5);
    margin-top: var(--s-7);
  }

  .art-fine {
    font-family: var(--t-mono); font-size: 11px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--c-fg-3);
    max-width: 68ch;
  }

  .art-foot {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--c-line);
    padding: var(--s-7) 0;
  }
  .art-foot-row {
    display: flex; justify-content: space-between;
    flex-wrap: wrap; gap: var(--s-3);
    font-family: var(--t-mono); font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--c-fg-2);
  }

  .seg .tbl { margin-top: var(--s-5); }
</style>
